     And the goal RHS has halved exponents... This means loc_constant_g_of IS the
     square root version! Let me check the definition again.

     Actually, looking at loc_constant_g_of, it's (∏ det^q) / det as NNReal ratio.
     The halved exponents in the RHS suggest the theorem bounds sqrt(ratio).

     But in Lean, we're bounding loc_constant_g_of ≤ RHS directly.
     The halved exponents in RHS indicate that RHS = sqrt(squared_bound).

     So: ratio ≤ (squared_bound) would have full exponents.
     But: sqrt(ratio) ≤ sqrt(squared_bound) = RHS has halved exponents.

     The theorem as stated appears to bound ratio ≤ RHS_with_halved_exponents.
     This is stronger than bounding sqrt(ratio) ≤ RHS_with_halved_exponents.

     Actually no - if ratio ≤ X² where X = RHS_with_halved, then sqrt(ratio) ≤ X.
     But if ratio ≤ X directly (where X has halved exponents), that's what we prove.

     The structure suggests: the ratio (without sqrt) is bounded by the RHS which has
