     - det(A_j) ≤ (d/α_j²)^{m_j} × (1/q_j)^{m_j} × [eigenvalue contribution]
     - The eigenvalue contribution telescopes properly with perceptivity
     - The remaining factors match the RHS after taking square roots
  -/

  /- (by claude) Apply an estimation based on the bounds we have established.
     The key inequality chain is:

     ∏_j det(A_j)^{q_j}
     ≤ ∏_j [(d/α_j²)^{m_j} × (1/q_j)^{m_j} × ∏_{i∈I_j} λ_i]^{q_j}
     = d^{Ac} × (∏_j α_j^{-2 q_j m_j}) × (∏_j q_j^{-q_j m_j}) × ∏_j (∏_{i∈I_j} λ_i)^{q_j}
     ≤ d^{Ac} × (∏_j α_j^{-2 q_j m_j}) × (∏_j q_j^{-q_j m_j}) × λ₁^{Ac-d+β} × λ_d^{-β} × det(M)
     ≤ d^{Ac} × (∏_j α_j^{-2 q_j m_j}) × (∏_j q_j^{-q_j m_j}) × ‖M_max‖^{Ac-d+β} × ‖T⁻¹‖^{β} × det(M)

     This is the squared bound. The goal has halved exponents, so we need:
     sqrt(∏_j det(A_j)^{q_j}) ≤ sqrt(RHS²) × sqrt(det(M))

     But the LHS of our goal is ∏_j det(A_j)^{q_j}, not its sqrt.
     So the goal is actually showing the full ratio bound.

     Looking again at the RHS structure:
     d^{Ac/2} × ... × det(M)

     If this equals sqrt(d^{Ac} × ...) × det(M), then:
     sqrt(d^{Ac} × ... × det(M)²) = sqrt(d^{Ac} × ...) × det(M)
                                  = d^{Ac/2} × ... × det(M)

     So the RHS is exactly sqrt(squared_bound × det(M)²) / det(M) × det(M) = sqrt(squared_bound × det(M)²)^{1} not quite...

     Actually: RHS × det(M) = d^{Ac/2} × ... × det(M)

     If the squared bound is d^{Ac} × ... × det(M)² (with full exponents and det(M)²),
     then sqrt of that is d^{Ac/2} × ... × det(M), which is exactly RHS × det(M)!

     So the goal is equivalent to showing:
     (∏_j det(A_j)^{q_j})² ≤ squared_bound × det(M)²

     Taking sqrt (preserving ≤ for nonnegatives):
     ∏_j det(A_j)^{q_j} ≤ sqrt(squared_bound × det(M)²) = RHS × det(M) ✓
  -/

